references:
For each dataset,
we follow (Grover and
Leskovec, 2016) to randomly hide 20% of edges of each edge type as missing edges.
Then, we learn the embedding using the rest of the 80% edges and predict these missing edges.
For the computational effciency, we randomly sample 2,048 edges (from the 20% hided edges) as positive examples and equally split them into two partitions Et​r​a​i​nsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑖𝑛E_{train} and Et​e​s​tsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡E_{test}.
We also randomly sample 2,048 unobserved edges as negative examples and equally split them into two partitions Et​r​a​i​n−superscriptsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑖𝑛E_{train}^{-} and Et​e​s​t−superscriptsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡E_{test}^{-}.
Then, we consider the link prediction evaluation as a binary classification problem with (Et​r​a​i​n,Et​r​a​i​n−)subscript𝐸𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑖𝑛superscriptsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑟𝑎𝑖𝑛(E_{train},E_{train}^{-}) for training and (Et​e​s​t,Et​e​s​t−)subscript𝐸𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡superscriptsubscript𝐸𝑡𝑒𝑠𝑡(E_{test},E_{test}^{-}) for testing.
We study several binary operators (Grover and
Leskovec, 2016) (as shown in Table 3) to construct features for an edge based on its two node vectors, and then the operated feature vector for an edge is as the input to a logistic regression classifier.
We repeat the above link prediction experiment ten times and report the average performance in terms of AUC (Area Under Curve) score.
